  "prompt": "What would be the quadratic equation for the roots 2+\u221a2 and 2-\u221a2?",
  "response": "To find the quadratic equation with roots \\( 2 + \\sqrt{2} \\) and \\( 2 - \\sqrt{2} \\), follow these steps:\n\n1. **Use the Sum and Product of Roots:**\n   \n   For a quadratic equation of the form:\n   \\[\n   x^2 - (\\text{sum of roots})x + (\\text{product of roots}) = 0\n   \\]\n   \n   - **Sum of the roots (S):**\n     \\[\n     (2 + \\sqrt{2}) + (2 - \\sqrt{2}) = 4\n     \\]\n   \n   - **Product of the roots (P):**\n     \\[\n     (2 + \\sqrt{2})(2 - \\sqrt{2}) = 2^2 - (\\sqrt{2})^2 = 4 - 2 = 2\n     \\]\n\n2. **Form the Quadratic Equation:**\n   \n   Substituting the sum and product into the standard form:\n   \\[\n   x^2 - Sx + P = 0 \\\\\n   x^2 - 4x + 2 = 0\n   \\]\n\n**Final Quadratic Equation:**\n\\[\n\\boxed{x^2 - 4x + 2 = 0}\n\\]",
